<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>TF-2 Graphs of Trigonometric Functions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers graphing the six trigonometric functions and transformation of them. 
      You should be able to graph the sine, cosine, tangent, cosecant, secant and cotangent 
      functions by hand. You should be able to identify the period, amplitude, reflections, phase 
      shift and vertical shift of a trigonometric function from its equation and use this information to graph the function.
      You should also be able to find the range, intercepts, and asymptotes of the trigonometric functions.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 1 problem. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Given a trigonometric function, identify the period, amplitude, reflections, phase 
        shift and vertical shift of the function.</p></li>
      <li><p> Use the equation to find the range, intercepts, and asymptotes of the function.</p></li>
      <li><p> Use the given information to find the five key features (points or asymptotes) on the principal 
        shifted period of the function.</p></li>
      <li><p>Graph the function on a given interval.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given the function: <m>y=-3\cos\left(\frac{3\pi x}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the five points that give the main features of the shifted principal period.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the principal period and the transformations to find the key points.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>(-\frac{2}{3}, -1), (0, 2), (\frac{2}{3}, 5), (\frac{4}{3}, 2), (2, -1)</m></p></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the range of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the range, consider the maximum and minimum values 
              of the cosine function along with the amplitude and any vertical 
              shift.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>The range is <m>[-1, 5]</m>.</p></answer>
            <solution><p>The cosine function oscillates between -1 and 1. 
              With an amplitude of 3, it oscillates between -3 and 3. 
              Adding the vertical shift of 2, the range becomes <m>[-1, 5]</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the amplitude of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The amplitude is the absolute value of the coefficient 
              of the cosine function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Amp=3</m></p></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the period of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The period is given by <m>\frac{2\pi}{|b|}</m> where 
              <m>b</m> is the coefficient of <m>x</m> in the argument of the 
              cosine function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Period = \frac{8}{3}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>p=\frac{2\pi}{|\frac{3\pi}{4}|}=\frac{8}{3}</m>
            </p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the phase shift of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The phase shift is given by <m>-\frac{c}{b}</m> where 
              <m>c</m> is the constant term in the argument of the cosine 
              function and <m>b</m> is the coefficient of <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Phase Shift = left \frac{2}{3}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>ps=-\frac{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3\pi}{4}}=-\frac{2}{3}</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the vertical shift of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The vertical shift is given by the constant term added to 
              the cosine function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Vertical Shift = 2</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>vs=2</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the intercepts of the function.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the intercepts, set the function equal to zero 
              and solve for x.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>(0,2),(\frac{4}{3\pi}\arccos\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)-\frac{2}{3}+\frac{8n}{3},0))</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><md>
              <mrow>y &amp;=-3\cos\left(\frac{3\pi(0)}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2</mrow>
              <mrow>y &amp;=-3\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2</mrow>
              <mrow>y &amp;=2</mrow>
            </md>
              <md>
              <mrow>-3\cos\left(\frac{3\pi x}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2 &amp;=0</mrow>
              <mrow> \cos\left(\frac{3\pi x}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2}\right) &amp;=\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{3\pi x}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2} &amp;=\pm \arccos\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)+2n\pi</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{3\pi x}{4} &amp;=\pm\arccos\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)+2n\pi-\frac{\pi}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x=\pm\frac{4}{3\pi}\arccos\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)+\frac{2}{3}+\frac{8n}{3}</mrow>
            </md></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Graph the function on the interval <m>[0, 2\pi]</m>.</p></statement>
            <answer><p><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-tf2a-sample">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-5,-5,10,10)">
                      <definition>f(x)="3*cos(3*pi*x/4 + pi/2) + 2"</definition>
                      <grid spacings="((-5,1,10),(-5,1,10))"/>
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                      <graph function="f"/>
                    </coordinates>
                <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph of the function shows the key features 
                    such as the amplitude, period, phase shift, and vertical 
                    shift. The graph oscillates between -1 and 5, with a period 
                    of 8/3 and a phase shift of 2/3 to the left. The vertical 
                    shift is 2.">
                  </annotation>
                </annotations>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure></image></p></answer>
        </task>
    </exercise> 
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given the function: <m>y=\tan\frac{2\pi}{3}\left(x+\frac{1}{3}\right)+2</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the five points/asymptotes that give the main features of the shifted principal period.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the principal period and the transformations to find the key points.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>x=-\frac{13}{12}, \left(-\frac{17}{24},1\right), \left(-\frac{1}{3}, 2\right), 
              \left(\frac{1}{3}, 2\right), \left(\frac{1}{24}, 3\right), x=\frac{5}{12}</m></p></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the range of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the range, consider the maximum and minimum values 
              of the cosine function along with the amplitude and any vertical 
              shift.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>The range is <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.</p></answer>
            <solution><p>The tangent function has a range of all real numbers, 
              so the range is <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the amplitude of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The amplitude is the absolute value of the coefficient 
              of the tangent function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Amp=1</m></p></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the period of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The period is given by <m>\frac{\pi}{|b|}</m> where 
              <m>b</m> is the coefficient of <m>x</m> in the argument of the 
              tangent function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Period = \frac{3}{2}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>p=\frac{\pi}{|\frac{2\pi}{3}|}=\frac{3}{2}</m>
            </p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the phase shift of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The phase shift is given by <m>c</m> where 
              <m>c</m> is the constant term in the argument inside of the tangent 
              function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Phase Shift = left \frac{1}{3}</m></p></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the vertical shift of the function</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The vertical shift is given by the constant term added to 
              the tangent function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>Vertical Shift = 2</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>vs=2</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the intercepts of the function.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the intercepts, set the function equal to zero 
              and solve for x.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\left(0,\tan\left(\frac{2\pi}{9}\right)+2\right),
              \left(-\frac{1}{3}+\frac{3}{2\pi}\arctan(-2)+\frac{3n}{2},0\right)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><md>
              <mrow>y&amp;=\tan\frac{2\pi}{3}\left(0+\frac{1}{3}\right)+2</mrow>
              <mrow>y&amp;=\tan\left(\frac{2\pi}{9}\right)+2</mrow>
            </md>
              <md>
              <mrow>\tan\frac{2\pi}{3}\left(x+\frac{1}{3}\right)+2 &amp;=0</mrow>
              <mrow> \tan\frac{2\pi}{3}\left(x+\frac{1}{3}\right) &amp;=-2</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{2\pi}{3}\left(x+\frac{1}{3}\right) &amp;=\arctan(-2)+n\pi</mrow>
              <mrow>x+\frac{1}{3} &amp;=\frac{3}{2\pi}\arctan(-2)+\frac{3n}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x &amp;=-\frac{1}{3}+\frac{3}{2\pi}\arctan(-2)+\frac{3n}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            </p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Graph the function on the interval <m>[0, 2\pi]</m>.</p></statement>
            <answer><p><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-tf2b-sample">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-5,-5,10,10)">
                      <definition>f(x)="tan(\frac{2\pi}{3}(x+\frac{1}{3}))+2"</definition>
                      <grid spacings="((-5,1,10),(-5,1,10))"/>
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                      <graph function="f"/>
                    </coordinates>
                <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph of the function shows the key features 
                    such as the amplitude, period, phase shift, and vertical 
                    shift. The graph has vertical asymptotes at x = 5/12 + 3n/2, 
                    where n is an integer.">
                  </annotation>
                </annotations>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure></image></p></answer>
        </task>
    </exercise> 
  </page>
</worksheet>